If you think buying art is just for the rich and famous…⁠
⁠
Like you need a house with marble floors, chandeliers, and an exotic pet roaming the halls…⁠

You, my friend, are mistaken.⁠

How can you add more FUN, JOY, and LIFE to your everyday?⁠
⁠
Aside from spontaneous dance parties, wet dog kisses, and breaking out the china on a Tuesday night…⁠
⁠
The simple answer is COLOR.⁠
⁠
Color is FUN 💃⁠
Color is JOY 😄⁠
Color is LIFE 💖⁠
⁠
And I want to help you add more of all those things to your world.⁠
⁠
Need help figuring out where to start? I’m only a DM away. 🌈

Feel the fear and do it anyway.

It’s a cliched saying, but I’m living proof that there’s something to it.

Back in the early 2000s (!) I hadn’t picked up a paintbrush in years. I felt a sudden drive to make art…but the fear was real. A little voice in me said, “Who do you think you are?”

I felt the imposter syndrome but I picked up that paintbrush anyway.

I painted a zillion pieces anyway.

I contacted big-time galleries anyway.

If I hadn’t ignored the fear, I wouldn’t be an artist, doing what I love every day.

So if you’ve got a dream and your fear is screaming, do the thing anyway. I'll be here for moral support. 😉
Because life is better with color ✨🌈

I know purchasing art can definitely feel like a splurge. But as a collector myself, I can tell you that there’s never any buyer’s remorse. Zero. Ever.

If you’re on the fence about buying, here are my top reasons why it’s worth it to take the leap:

💓 A unique piece can make your heart beat fast and fill you with joy (literally every time you walk past it)
👐 It feels really special in our mass-produced world to own something one-of-a-kind, made by hand (aka not Amazon Primed)
👩‍🎨You’re supporting a hard-working artist (not some cheap factory)
💰On the rational side, it’s simply a smart investment (cha-ching!)

I know how much love and creative sweat goes into any kind of artistry. Trust me…having someone support that endeavor is the most meaningful thing in the world. So if you were choosing between an independent artist’s work and some piece you found on Amazon…well…you know where I stand 😉

Does buying art online make you nervous? Don’t be scared…everybody’s doing it (seriously).

Online sales of art and antiques were estimated at $5.9 billion in 2019, according to @artbasel. It’s just how people shop art now. Thanks to Covid, that number has probably risen way higher.

I know buying art online can feel scary, so I’m there to hold your hand. I’ll share hi-res images, a video of the piece (so you can see it from all angles), and make sure that it’s packaged and shipped like glass.

So excited to share a special release of round fine art prints on METAL….these are available for a limited time in the Vault and come ready to hang…no framing needed. (Not to mention makes this series one of my most affordable too!)

As an artist, I have long been captivated by the power that this simple, yet infinitely complex shape holds. The circle, with its boundless continuity and lack of corners, represents unity, wholeness, and harmony.

By eliminating the traditional boundaries of a rectangular frame, I aim to blur the lines between art and sculpture, as each piece stands proudly as a three-dimensional work of art.

Congrats to the Lake Forest High School Sailing team! Repost from @cityoflakeforestil...

Lake Forest Sailing is going to New Orleans in pursuit of the National trophy!🏆

With a victory in the Midwest Scholastic Sailing Nationals Qualifier for the Cressy Trophy that it hosted Sept. 16-17, Lake Forest Sailing is heading to Nationals in October.⛵

Out of 54 competitors from across the Midwest, Lake Forest High School (LFHS) and Lake Forest Academy featured 10 sailors. Lake Forest Sailing swept the boys International Laser Class Association (ILCA) 6 and ILCA 7 qualifying spots.👏

Owen Kohut (Lake Forest High School '25) won the ILCA 6 with first-place finishes in each of the seven races, Alec Ranker (LFHS '24) finished second. Tristan McDonald (LFHS '24) won the ILCA 7 fleet, and teammate Charlie Gish (LFHS '24) finished second. Rounding out the podium in those fleets were Jackson Schwartz (LFHS '25) in the ILCA 6 and Matthew Sexton (Lake Forest Academy '24) in the ILCA 7.

“The regatta was great, and I am happy with my result, but the job is not yet done,” Kohut said.

Find the full story on the City's Lake Forest Love blog at LakeForestLove.com or visit our link in bio.🔗

So excited to be on the Kelly Clarkson Show tomorrow!! Tune in to see the big Hapi Art Green room reveal and watch me attempt to demo how to make my signature 3D Bloom art with Kelly and her celebrity guests! 

When I got the call that The Kelly Clarkson Show was moving to NYC to the iconic 30 Rock and that Kelly and the team wanted all of the green rooms to be Hapi Art, I was so thrilled!! 

This has been a labor of love and it was such a JOY to only get to see everything come to life, but to be a guest on the show! (and thankfully no one was the least bit shy about using the glitter!)

Just so we’re clear: When you purchase any piece from Hapi Art, you’re buying directly from me—the artist.

There’s no middleman, no gallery that gets a cut, no cheap factory churning out reproductions of my work. It’s just me (and my awesome team of assistants and framers) prepping and sending the work straight to your door.

To be sure there’s no doubt about it, each piece comes with a Certificate of Authenticity showing that the work originates from my studio. 

There are a lot of places to buy art out there, but they’re not all authentic. So I just wanted to get out my bullhorn for a moment. 📢
